>
  <p>
    For as long as retail investors have been able to buy startup shares, the
    exit question has had an awkward answer: <em>you probably can't sell until
    the company sells.</em> Private shares had no regulated place to trade, liquidity was a patchwork of one-off platform events, broker-matched blocks
    and luck.
  </p>
  <p>
    That changed with <strong>PISCES</strong>, the Private Intermittent
    Securities and Capital Exchange System, the UK framework for regulated
    trading of private company shares. By spring 2026, three routes were
    approved: the London Stock Exchange's Private Securities Market, which
    opened with an Oxford Science Enterprises auction; JP Jenkins, which reaches
    earlier-stage companies through ordinary brokerage accounts with CREST
    settlement; and Asset Match's periodic auction model.
  </p>

  <h2>The design insight: intermittent, not continuous</h2>
  <p>
    The most important word in PISCES is <em>intermittent</em>. These are not
    stock exchanges for startups. Trading happens in scheduled windows, auctions at intervals a company chooses, rather than continuously.
  </p>
  <p>
    That design is a quiet piece of investor protection. Continuous markets in
    illiquid, information-poor assets mostly manufacture bad prices and worse
    behaviour: thin order books, stale valuations, day-trading impulses applied
    to assets that reprice on quarterly board updates. Concentrating liquidity
    into windows, with company disclosure refreshed beforehand, gives price
    discovery a fighting chance and removes the casino mechanics entirely.
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    A liquidity window is a scheduled opportunity, not a promise. The honest
    framing is "you may be able to sell, sometimes", never "your shares are
    now liquid."
  </blockquote>

  <h2>What windows genuinely change</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Employees and early investors get a lawful, orderly route to
      partial liquidity</strong>, the use case the LSE's first auctions were
      built around.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Price discovery improves.</strong> A cleared auction price,
      however imperfect, beats a number from the last funding round two years
      ago.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Platforms can plan around liquidity</strong>, scheduled windows
      make holding-period conversations honest: "the next window is October,"
      not "someday, maybe."
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What they don't change</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Demand is not guaranteed.</strong> A window with no buyers clears
      nothing. Early-stage shares may see no window at all, companies opt in,
      and many won't.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The risk profile of the asset.</strong> A startup share bought in
      a window can still go to zero on Tuesday. Total-loss risk survives
      regulation intact.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Tax reliefs don't follow.</strong> SEIS/EIS reliefs attach to
      qualifying <em>new</em> shares; buying second-hand in a window generally
      earns none of them, a detail that materially changes the downside maths
      versus primary investing.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The missing layer: who should be trading?</h2>
  <p>
    Here is what strikes us most about the PISCES era so far. Every serious
    player is racing to add <em>access</em> to liquidity, venues, partnerships,
    retail gateways. Almost nobody is asking the suitability question:
    <strong>should this particular investor be making this particular
    trade?</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Selling a position changes a portfolio just as buying does. A retail
    investor selling their one winner in a liquidity window may be turning a
    diversified portfolio back into a concentrated one, locking in the
    survivorship and keeping the risk. A buyer picking up secondary shares at a
    premium, with no relief eligibility, may be taking primary-market risk at
    worse economics without noticing.
  </p>
  <p>
    That's the gap Bundle's <a href="/secondary-market">secondary market
    design</a> exists to fill: structured windows <em>plus</em> a discipline
    layer, suitability checks on both sides, a concentration-impact preview
    before any order, and refreshed plain-English disclosure as standard. As far
    as we can tell, nobody else in the UK is pairing private-market liquidity
    with suitability. We think that pairing is the whole point.
  </p>

  <h2>What to do with this, today</h2>
  <p>
    If you hold private shares: find out whether your platform or company plans
    PISCES participation, and treat any window as optional, not owed. If you're
    building a portfolio: keep assuming 5–10 year holds, windows are a bonus
    scenario in your planning, never the base case. And if a platform's
    marketing implies startup shares are now "tradable like stocks," close the
    tab.
  </p>

